  "title": "LETS From a Feature Phone Discussion",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f903182ab6af6b4d",
      "text": "QUESTION: How can LETS currency work, even though it is so different from real money?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0b96330d7b6fdaf8",
      "text": "You see, we've all been using 'hard' currencies and nothing else for so long that we've forgotten that money is just a game. Those bits of paper really are just bits of paper - they're not worth anything really. They only have value of the person you want to trade in believes that they are valuable. And in fact they're only really valuable if many people believe in them."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7ae1a36d2b458857",
      "text": "In places where people stop believing that, money becomes worthless. In Germany, in the 1930s, there's a story that money was so worthless, it took a wheelbarrow load of notes to buy a loaf of bread. Someone was robbed - they stole the wheelbarrow and left the notes behind - the wheelbarrow was worth more than the notes."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d1b927bdba63c0b6",
      "text": "So LETS currency depends on whether people believe in the marketplace it works in. Because LETS currency usually only works in that marketplace. This can be a good thing and a bad thing."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "39ae95952458de54",
      "text": "The good thing is that the LETS money stays in the community that uses the marketplace. In many places money spent in a shop immediately goes off to the big company that owns the shop. It disappears from the community. And since money only does any good when it changes hands, then it stops doing any good in that community - it can't change hands there when it has gone somewhere else. Money that stays in a community goes round and round, doing something useful every time it changes hands."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3619cfa3123edae4",
      "text": "The bad thing is that it can be hard to use LETS currency to buy things that are made outside the marketplace community. We might all be farmers and builders. So we might have a good marketplace for food and labour and getting walls built. But our currency might not be much use to buy fertiliser or glass. These are made in factories somewhere else, and the people that deal with the factories have to pay in hard currency."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0cfde1e02fbf7863",
      "text": "This is a real issue, but the good news is that the bigger and stronger our marketplace is, the easier it gets. We might just have to accept that we start with things that we can make, do and swap ourselves, and work to grow our marketplace until the dealers in factory made stuff are willing to join us - which will be when they know that they can get all sorts of things that they need from our marketplace."
    }
